[src:fastify/fastify] As a lightweight alternative to other Node.js web API frameworks, benchmarks reveal it to be significantly faster.
[src:fastify/fastify] Fastify was first conceived by Matteo Collina in 2015, and created together with Tomas Della Vedova in September 2016.
[src:fastify/fastify] According to GitHub, the initial release of Fastify was version 0.1.0 on October 17, 2016.
[src:fastify/fastify] Building upon the technical foundations of Fastify, Collina and Luca Maraschi created Platformatic in 2022, to support a "batteries-included" developer experience for building APIs (REST/OpenAPI or GraphQL).
[src:fastify/fastify] In 2023, *Accelerating Server-Side Development with Fastify*, a comprehensive guide authored by Fastify core contributors, was published.
[src:fastify/fastify] Some users of Fastify include Capital One, Walmart, American Express.
[src:fastify/getting-started] This document aims to be a gentle introduction to the framework and its features.
[src:fastify/getting-started] It is an elementary preface with examples and links to other parts of the documentation.
[src:fastify/getting-started] Unfortunately, writing a complex application requires significantly more code than this example.
[src:fastify/getting-started] A classic problem when you are building a new application is how to handle multiple files, asynchronous bootstrapping, and the architecture of your code.
[src:fastify/getting-started] Fastify offers an easy platform that helps to solve all of the problems outlined above, and more!
[src:fastify/getting-started] As with JavaScript, where everything is an object, with Fastify everything is a plugin.
[src:fastify/getting-started] Before digging into it, let's see how it works!
[src:fastify/getting-started] Let's declare our basic server, but instead of declaring the route inside the entry point, we'll declare it in an external file (check out the route declaration docs).
[src:fastify/getting-started] In this example, we used the `register` API, which is the core of the Fastify framework.
[src:fastify/getting-started] It is the only way to add routes, plugins, et cetera.
[src:fastify/getting-started] At the beginning of this guide, we noted that Fastify provides a foundation that assists with asynchronous bootstrapping of your application.
[src:fastify/getting-started] Consider the scenario where a database connection is needed to handle data storage.
[src:fastify/getting-started] The database connection needs to be available before the server is accepting connections.
[src:fastify/getting-started] A typical solution is to use a complex callback, or promises - a system that will mix the framework API with other libraries and the application code.
[src:fastify/getting-started] Fastify handles this internally, with minimum effort!
[src:fastify/getting-started] Let's rewrite the above example with a database connection.
[src:fastify/getting-started] Let's recap what we have done here since we've introduced some new concepts.
[src:fastify/getting-started] As you can see, we used `register` for both the database connector and the registration of the routes.
[src:fastify/getting-started] This is one of the best features of Fastify, it will load your plugins in the same order you declare them, and it will load the next plugin only once the current one has been loaded.
[src:fastify/getting-started] In this way, we can register the database connector in the first plugin and use it in the second *(read here to understand how to handle the scope of a plugin)*.
[src:fastify/getting-started] The MongoDB plugin uses the `decorate` API to add custom objects to the Fastify instance, making them available for use everywhere.
[src:fastify/getting-started] Use of this API is encouraged to facilitate easy code reuse and to decrease code or logic duplication.
[src:fastify/getting-started] To dig deeper into how Fastify plugins work, how to develop new plugins, and for details on how to use the whole Fastify API to deal with the complexity of asynchronously bootstrapping an application, read the hitchhiker's guide to plugins.
[src:fastify/getting-started] In this way, you will always have access to all of the properties declared in the current scope.
[src:fastify/getting-started] As discussed previously, Fastify offers a solid encapsulation model, to help you build your application as independent services.
[src:fastify/getting-started] If you want to register a plugin only for a subset of routes, you just have to replicate the above structure.
[src:fastify/getting-started] Data validation is extremely important and a core concept of the framework.
[src:fastify/getting-started] To validate incoming requests, Fastify uses JSON Schema.
[src:fastify/getting-started] This example shows how to pass an options object to the route, which accepts a `schema` key that contains all of the schemas for route, `body`, `querystring`, `params`, and `headers`.
[src:fastify/getting-started] Read Validation and Serialization to learn more.
[src:fastify/getting-started] Fastify has first-class support for JSON.
[src:fastify/getting-started] It is extremely optimized to parse JSON bodies and serialize JSON output.
[src:fastify/getting-started] By specifying a schema as shown, you can speed up serialization by a factor of 2-3.
[src:fastify/getting-started] This also helps to protect against leakage of potentially sensitive data, since Fastify will serialize only the data present in the response schema.
[src:fastify/getting-started] Fastify parses `'application/json'` and `'text/plain'` request payloads natively, with the result accessible from the Fastify request object at `request.body`.
[src:fastify/getting-started] Read Content-Type Parser to learn more about Fastify's default parsing functionality and how to support other content types.
[src:fastify/getting-started] Fastify is built to be extremely extensible and minimal, we believe that a bare-bones framework is all that is necessary to make great applications possible.
[src:fastify/getting-started] In other words, Fastify is not a "batteries included" framework, and relies on an amazing ecosystem!
[src:fastify/getting-started] Fastify does not offer a testing framework, but we do recommend a way to write your tests that uses the features and architecture of Fastify.
[src:fastify/getting-started] Read the testing documentation to learn more!
[src:fastify/getting-started] Fastify also has CLI integration via fastify-cli, a separate tool for scaffolding and managing Fastify projects.
[src:fastify/getting-started] You can also install it globally with `-g`.
[src:fastify/json-schema] JSON is a programming language-independent data format.
[src:fastify/json-schema] It was derived from JavaScript, but many modern programming languages include code to generate and parse JSON-format data.
[src:fastify/json-schema] JSON filenames use the extension `.json`.
[src:fastify/json-schema] Douglas Crockford originally specified the JSON format in the early 2000s.
[src:fastify/json-schema] They and Chip Morningstar sent the first JSON message in April 2001.
[src:fastify/json-schema] The 2017 international standard (ECMA-404 and ISO/IEC 21778:2017) specifies that "JSON" is "pronounced /ˈdʒeɪ.sən/, as in 'Jason and The Argonauts'".
[src:fastify/json-schema] The first (2013) edition of ECMA-404 did not address the pronunciation.
[src:fastify/json-schema] Crockford said in 2011, "There's a lot of argument about how you pronounce that, but I strictly don't care." /ˈdʒeɪˌsɒn/ is another common pronunciation.
[src:fastify/json-schema] After RFC 4627 had been available as its "informational" specification since 2006, JSON was first standardized in 2013, as ECMA-404.
[src:fastify/json-schema] RFC 8259, published in 2017, is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90, and it remains consistent with ECMA-404.
[src:fastify/json-schema] That same year, JSON was also standardized as ISO/IEC 21778:2017.
[src:fastify/json-schema] The ECMA and ISO/IEC standards describe only the allowed syntax, whereas the RFC covers some security and interoperability considerations.
[src:fastify/json-schema] JSON grew out of a need for a real-time server-to-browser session communication protocol without using browser plugins such as Flash or Java applets, the dominant methods used in the early 2000s.
[src:fastify/json-schema] Crockford first specified and popularized the JSON format.
[src:fastify/json-schema] The acronym originated at State Software, a company cofounded by Crockford and others in March 2001.
[src:fastify/json-schema] The cofounders had a round-table discussion and voted on whether to call the data format JSML (JavaScript Markup Language) or JSON (JavaScript Object Notation), as well as under what license type to make it available.
[src:fastify/json-schema] The JSON.org website was launched in 2001.
[src:fastify/json-schema] In December 2005, Yahoo! began offering some of its Web services in JSON.
[src:fastify/json-schema] A precursor to the JSON libraries was used in a children's digital asset trading game project named Cartoon Orbit at Communities.com which used a browser side plug-in with a proprietary messaging format to manipulate DHTML elements.
[src:fastify/json-schema] Crockford then found that JavaScript could be used as an object-based messaging format for such a system.
[src:fastify/json-schema] The system was sold to Sun Microsystems, Amazon.com, and EDS.
[src:fastify/json-schema] JSON was based on a subset of the JavaScript scripting language (specifically, Standard ECMA-262 3rd Edition—December 1999) and is commonly used with JavaScript, but it is a language-independent data format.
[src:fastify/json-schema] Code for parsing and generating JSON data is readily available in many programming languages.
[src:fastify/json-schema] JSON's website lists JSON libraries by language.
[src:fastify/json-schema] In October 2013, Ecma International published the first edition of its JSON standard ECMA-404.
[src:fastify/json-schema] That same year, RFC 7158 used ECMA-404 as a reference.
[src:fastify/json-schema] In 2014, RFC 7159 became the main reference for JSON's Internet uses, superseding RFC 4627 and RFC 7158 (but preserving ECMA-262 and ECMA-404 as main references).
[src:fastify/json-schema] In November 2017, ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 22 published ISO/IEC 21778:2017 as an international standard.
[src:fastify/json-schema] On December 13, 2017, the Internet Engineering Task Force obsoleted RFC 7159 when it published RFC 8259, which is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90.
[src:fastify/json-schema] Crockford added a clause to the JSON license stating, "The Software shall be used for Good, not Evil", in order to open-source the JSON libraries while mocking corporate lawyers and those who are overly pedantic.
[src:fastify/json-schema] On the other hand, this clause led to license compatibility problems of the JSON license with other open-source licenses since open-source software and free software usually imply no restrictions on the purpose of use.
[src:fastify/json-schema] The following example shows a possible JSON representation describing a person.
[src:fastify/json-schema] This is a consequence of JSON disallowing only "control characters".
[src:fastify/json-schema] For maximum portability, these characters are backslash-escaped.
[src:fastify/json-schema] JSON exchange in an open ecosystem must be encoded in UTF-8.
[src:fastify/json-schema] The encoding supports the full Unicode character set, including those characters outside the Basic Multilingual Plane (U+0000 to U+FFFF).
[src:fastify/json-schema] However, if escaped, those characters must be written using UTF-16 surrogate pairs.
[src:fastify/json-schema] JSON became a strict subset of ECMAScript as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:fastify/json-schema] Whitespace is allowed and ignored around or between syntactic elements (values and punctuation, but not within a string value).
[src:fastify/json-schema] Four specific characters are considered whitespace for this purpose: space, horizontal tab, line feed, and carriage return.
[src:fastify/json-schema] In particular, the byte order mark must not be generated by a conforming implementation (though it may be accepted when parsing JSON).
[src:fastify/json-schema] JSON does not provide syntax for comments.
[src:fastify/json-schema] Early versions of JSON (such as specified by RFC 4627) required that a valid JSON text must consist of only an object or an array type, which could contain other types within them.
[src:fastify/json-schema] This restriction was dropped in RFC 7158, where a JSON text was redefined as any serialized value.
[src:fastify/json-schema] Numbers in JSON are agnostic with regard to their representation within programming languages.
[src:fastify/json-schema] While this allows for numbers of arbitrary precision to be serialized, it may lead to portability issues.
[src:fastify/json-schema] For example, since no differentiation is made between integer and floating-point values, some implementations may treat `42`, `42.0`, and `4.2E+1` as the same number, while others may not.
[src:fastify/json-schema] The JSON standard makes no requirements regarding implementation details such as overflow, underflow, loss of precision, rounding, or signed zeros, but it does recommend expecting no more than IEEE 754 binary64 precision for "good interoperability".
[src:fastify/json-schema] There is no inherent precision loss in serializing a machine-level binary representation of a floating-point number (like binary64) into a human-readable decimal representation (like numbers in JSON) and back; there exist published algorithms to do this conversion exactly and optimally.
[src:fastify/json-schema] Comments were intentionally excluded from JSON.
[src:fastify/json-schema] JSON disallows "trailing commas", a comma after the last value inside a data structure.
[src:fastify/json-schema] Trailing commas are a common feature of JSON derivatives to improve ease of use.
[src:fastify/json-schema] RFC 8259 describes certain aspects of JSON syntax that, while legal per the specifications, can cause interoperability problems.
[src:fastify/json-schema] In 2015, the IETF published RFC 7493, describing the "I-JSON Message Format", a restricted profile of JSON that constrains the syntax and processing of JSON to avoid, as much as possible, these interoperability issues.
[src:fastify/json-schema] While JSON provides a syntactic framework for data interchange, unambiguous data interchange also requires agreement between producer and consumer on the semantics of specific use of the JSON syntax.
[src:fastify/json-schema] One example of where such an agreement is necessary is the serialization of data types that are not part of the JSON standard, for example, dates and regular expressions.
[src:fastify/json-schema] The official MIME type for JSON text is `application/json`, and most modern implementations have adopted this.
[src:fastify/json-schema] Legacy MIME types include `text/json`, `text/x-json`, and `text/javascript`.
[src:fastify/json-schema] The standard filename extension is .json.
[src:fastify/json-schema] The JSON standard does not support object references, but an IETF draft standard for JSON-based object references exists.
[src:fastify/json-schema] JSON-RPC is a remote procedure call (RPC) protocol built on JSON, as a replacement for XML-RPC or SOAP.
[src:fastify/json-schema] It is a simple protocol that defines only a handful of data types and commands.
[src:fastify/json-schema] JSON-RPC lets a system send notifications (information to the server that does not require a response) and multiple calls to the server that can be answered out of order.
[src:fastify/json-schema] Asynchronous JavaScript and JSON (or AJAJ) refers to the same dynamic web page methodology as Ajax, but instead of XML, JSON is the data format.
[src:fastify/json-schema] AJAJ is a web development technique that provides for the ability of a web page to request new data after it has loaded into the web browser.
[src:fastify/json-schema] Typically, it renders new data from the server in response to user actions on that web page.
[src:fastify/json-schema] For example, what the user types into a search box, client-side code then sends to the server, which immediately responds with a drop-down list of matching database items.
[src:fastify/json-schema] JSON has seen ad hoc usage as a configuration language.
[src:fastify/json-schema] In 2012, Douglas Crockford, JSON creator, had this to say about comments in JSON when used as a configuration language: "I know that the lack of comments makes some people sad, but it shouldn't.
[src:fastify/json-schema] Suppose you are using JSON to keep configuration files, which you would like to annotate.
[src:fastify/json-schema] Go ahead and insert all the comments you like.
[src:fastify/json-schema] MongoDB uses JSON-like data for its document-oriented database.
[src:fastify/json-schema] Some relational databases have added support for native JSON data types, such as JSONB in PostgreSQL and JSON in MySQL.
[src:fastify/json-schema] This allows developers to insert JSON data directly without having to convert it to another format.
[src:fastify/json-schema] JSON being a subset of JavaScript can lead to the misconception that it is safe to pass JSON texts to the JavaScript `eval()` function.
[src:fastify/json-schema] This is not safe, due to certain valid JSON texts, specifically those containing U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR or U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR, not being valid JavaScript code until JavaScript specifications were updated in 2019, and so older engines may not support it.
[src:fastify/json-schema] To avoid the many pitfalls caused by executing arbitrary code from the Internet, a new function, `JSON.parse()`, was first added to the fifth edition of ECMAScript, which as of 2017 is supported by all major browsers.
[src:fastify/json-schema] For non-supported browsers, an API-compatible JavaScript library is provided by Douglas Crockford.
[src:fastify/json-schema] In addition, the TC39 proposal "Subsume JSON" made ECMAScript a strict JSON superset as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:fastify/json-schema] Various JSON parser implementations have suffered from denial-of-service attack and mass assignment vulnerability.
[src:fastify/json-schema] JSON is promoted as a low-overhead alternative to XML as both of these formats have widespread support for creation, reading, and decoding in the real-world situations where they are commonly used.
[src:fastify/json-schema] XML has been used to describe structured data and to serialize objects.
[src:fastify/json-schema] Various XML-based protocols exist to represent the same kind of data structures as JSON for the same kind of data interchange purposes.
[src:fastify/json-schema] Data can be encoded in XML in several ways.
[src:fastify/json-schema] The most expansive form using tag pairs results in a much larger (in character count) representation than JSON, but if data is stored in attributes and *short tag* form where the closing tag is replaced with `/>`, the representation is often about the same size as JSON or just a little larger.
[src:fastify/json-schema] However, an XML attribute can only have a single value and each attribute can appear at most once on each element.
[src:fastify/json-schema] XML separates data from metadata (via the use of elements and attributes), while JSON does not have such a concept.
[src:fastify/json-schema] Another key difference is the addressing of values.
[src:fastify/json-schema] JSON has objects with a simple key-to-value mapping, whereas in XML addressing happens on *nodes*, each of which receives a unique ID via the XML processor.
[src:fastify/json-schema] Additionally, the XML standard defines a common attribute `xml:id`, that can be used by the user, to set an ID explicitly.
[src:fastify/json-schema] XML tag names cannot contain any of the characters !"#$%&'()*+,/;<=>?@[\]^`{|}~, nor a space character, and cannot begin with `-`, `.`, or a numeric digit, whereas JSON keys can (even if quotation mark and backslash must be escaped).
[src:fastify/json-schema] XML values are strings of *characters*, with no built-in type safety.
[src:fastify/json-schema] XML has the concept of schema, that permits strong typing, user-defined types, predefined tags, and formal structure, allowing for formal validation of an XML stream.
[src:fastify/json-schema] JSON has several types built-in and has a similar schema concept in JSON Schema.
[src:fastify/json-schema] XML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:fastify/json-schema] Support for comments and other features have been deemed useful, which has led to several nonstandard JSON supersets being created.
[src:fastify/json-schema] Among them are HJSON, HOCON, and JSON5 (which despite its name, is not the fifth version of JSON).
[src:fastify/json-schema] YAML version 1.2 is a superset of JSON; prior versions were not strictly compatible.
[src:fastify/json-schema] For example, escaping a slash `/` with a backslash `\` is valid in JSON, but was not valid in YAML.
[src:fastify/json-schema] YAML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:fastify/json-schema] There is also an unrelated project called **CSON** ("Cursive Script Object Notation") that is more syntactically similar to JSON.
[src:fastify/json-schema] JSON5 syntax is supported in some software as an extension of JSON syntax, for instance in SQLite.
[src:fastify/json-schema] Several serialization formats have been built on or from the JSON specification.
[src:fastify/node-js] Node.js allows developers to use JavaScript for writing command line tools and server-side scripting.
[src:fastify/node-js] Running Javascript on the server is commonly used to generate dynamic web page content before the page is sent to the user's web browser.
[src:fastify/node-js] Consequently, Node.js represents a "JavaScript everywhere" paradigm, unifying web-application development around a single programming language, as opposed to using different languages for the server- versus client-side programming.
[src:fastify/node-js] Node.js has an event-driven architecture capable of asynchronous I/O.
[src:fastify/node-js] These design choices aim to optimize throughput and scalability in web applications with many input/output operations, as well as for real-time Web applications (e.g., real-time communication programs and browser games).
[src:fastify/node-js] The Node.js distributed development project was previously governed by the Node.js Foundation, and has now merged with the JS Foundation to form the OpenJS Foundation.
[src:fastify/node-js] OpenJS Foundation is facilitated by the Linux Foundation's Collaborative Projects program.
[src:fastify/node-js] Node.js was initially written by Ryan Dahl in 2009, about 13 years after the introduction of the first server-side JavaScript environment, Netscape's LiveWire Pro Web.
[src:fastify/node-js] The initial release supported only Linux and Mac OS X.
[src:fastify/node-js] Its development and maintenance was led by Dahl and later sponsored by Joyent.
[src:fastify/node-js] Dahl demonstrated the project at the inaugural European JSConf on November 8, 2009.
[src:fastify/node-js] Node.js combined Google's V8 JavaScript engine, an event loop, and a low-level I/O API.
[src:fastify/node-js] In January 2010, a package manager was introduced for the Node.js environment called npm.
[src:fastify/node-js] The package manager allows programmers to publish and share Node.js packages, along with the accompanying source code, and is designed to simplify the installation, update and uninstallation of packages.
[src:fastify/node-js] In June 2011, Microsoft and Joyent implemented a native Windows version of Node.js.
[src:fastify/node-js] The first Node.js build supporting Windows was released in July 2011.
[src:fastify/node-js] In January 2012, Dahl yielded management of the project to npm creator Isaac Schlueter.
[src:fastify/node-js] In January 2014, Schlueter announced that Timothy J.
[src:fastify/node-js] In December 2014, Fedor Indutny created io.js, a fork of Node.js created because of dissatisfaction with Joyent's governance as an open-governance alternative with a separate technical committee.
[src:fastify/node-js] The goal was to enable a structure that would be more receptive to community input, including the updating of io.js with the latest Google V8 JavaScript engine releases, diverging from Node.js's approach at that time.
[src:fastify/node-js] The Node.js Foundation, formed to reconcile Node.js and io.js under a unified banner, was announced in February 2015.
[src:fastify/node-js] The merger was realized in September 2015 with Node.js v0.12 and io.js v3.3 combining into Node v4.0.
[src:fastify/node-js] This merge brought V8 ES6 features into Node.js and started a long-term support release cycle.
[src:fastify/node-js] By 2016, the io.js website recommended returning to Node.js and announced no further io.js releases, effectively ending the fork and solidifying the merger's success.
[src:fastify/node-js] In 2019, the JS Foundation and Node.js Foundation merged to form the OpenJS Foundation.
[src:fastify/node-js] The Node.js logo features a green hexagon with overlapping bands to represent the cross-platform nature of the runtime.
[src:fastify/node-js] The Rocket Turtle was chosen as the official Node.js mascot in February 2024 following a design contest.
[src:fastify/node-js] Node.js allows the creation of web servers and networking tools using JavaScript and a collection of "modules" that handle various core functionalities.
[src:fastify/node-js] Modules are provided for file system I/O, networking (DNS, HTTP, TCP, TLS/SSL or UDP), binary data (buffers), cryptography functions, data streams and other core functions.
[src:fastify/node-js] Node.js's modules use an API designed to reduce the complexity of writing server applications.
[src:fastify/node-js] Since version 22.6.0, Node.js natively supports both JavaScript and TypeScript, allowing TypeScript files to be executed without a separate compilation step.
[src:fastify/node-js] The TypeScript support was contributed by Node.js TSC member Marco Ippolito.
[src:fastify/node-js] In addition, many compile-to-JS languages are available, allowing Node.js applications to also be written in CoffeeScript, Dart, ClojureScript, and others.
[src:fastify/node-js] Node.js is primarily used to build network programs such as web servers.
[src:fastify/node-js] The most significant difference between Node.js and PHP is that most functions in PHP block until completion (commands execute only after previous commands finish), while Node.js functions are non-blocking (commands execute concurrently and use callbacks to signal completion or failure).
[src:fastify/node-js] Node.js is officially supported by Linux, macOS and Microsoft Windows 8.1 and Server 2012 (and later), with Tier 2 support for SmartOS and IBM AIX and experimental support for FreeBSD.
[src:fastify/node-js] OpenBSD also works, and LTS versions are available for IBM i (AS/400).
[src:fastify/node-js] The source code may also be built on similar operating systems that are not officially supported, such as NonStop OS and Unix servers.
[src:fastify/node-js] Node.js enables development of fast web servers in JavaScript using event-driven programming.
[src:fastify/node-js] Developers can create scalable servers without using threading by using a simplified model that uses callbacks to signal the completion of a task.
[src:fastify/node-js] Node.js connects the ease of a scripting language (JavaScript) with the power of Unix network programming.
[src:fastify/node-js] Node.js was built on top of Google's V8 JavaScript engine since it was open-sourced under the BSD license, and it contains comprehensive support for fundamental protocols such as HTTP, DNS and TCP.
[src:fastify/node-js] JavaScript's existing popularity made Node.js accessible to the web-development community.
[src:fastify/node-js] There are thousands of open-source libraries for Node.js, most of which are hosted on the npm website.
[src:fastify/node-js] Multiple developer conferences and events are held that support the Node.js community, including NodeConf, Node Interactive, and Node Summit, as well as a number of regional events.
[src:fastify/node-js] The open-source community has developed web frameworks to accelerate the development of applications.
[src:fastify/node-js] Such frameworks include Express.js, Socket.IO, Sails.js, Next.js and Meteor.
[src:fastify/node-js] Various packages have also been created for interfacing with other languages or runtime environments such as Microsoft .NET.
[src:fastify/node-js] Modern desktop IDEs provide editing and debugging features specifically for Node.js applications.
[src:fastify/node-js] Such IDEs include Atom, Brackets, JetBrains WebStorm, Microsoft Visual Studio (with Node.js Tools for Visual Studio, or TypeScript with Node definitions), NetBeans, Nodeclipse Enide Studio (Eclipse-based) and Visual Studio Code.
[src:fastify/node-js] Some online IDEs also support Node.js, such as Codeanywhere, Eclipse Che, Cloud9 IDE and the visual flow editor in Node-RED.
[src:fastify/node-js] Node.js is supported across a number of cloud-hosting platforms such as Jelastic, Google Cloud Platform, AWS Elastic Beanstalk, Azure Web Apps and Joyent.
[src:fastify/node-js] New major releases of Node.js are cut from the GitHub main branch every six months.
[src:fastify/node-js] Even-numbered versions are cut in April and odd-numbered versions are cut in October.
[src:fastify/node-js] When a new odd version is released, the previous even version undergoes transition to Long Term Support (LTS), which gives that version 12 months of active support from the date it is designated LTS.
[src:fastify/node-js] After these 12 months expire, an LTS release receives an additional 18 months of maintenance support.
[src:fastify/node-js] An active version receives non-breaking backports of changes a few weeks after they land in the current release.
[src:fastify/node-js] A maintenance release receives only critical fixes and documentation updates.
[src:fastify/node-js] The LTS Working Group manages strategy and policy in collaboration with the Technical Steering Committee of the Node.js Foundation.
[src:fastify/node-js] Node.js is a JavaScript runtime environment that processes incoming requests in a loop, called the event loop.
[src:fastify/node-js] Node.js uses libuv under the hood to handle asynchronous events.
[src:fastify/node-js] Libuv is an abstraction layer for network and file system functionality on both Windows and POSIX-based systems such as Linux, macOS, OSS on NonStop, and Unix.
[src:fastify/node-js] Node.js relies on nghttp2 for HTTP support.
[src:fastify/node-js] As of version 20, Node.js uses the ada library which provides up-to-date WHATWG URL compliance.
[src:fastify/node-js] As of version 19.5, Node.js uses the simdutf library for fast Unicode validation and transcoding.
[src:fastify/node-js] As of version 21.3, Node.js uses the simdjson library for fast JSON parsing.
[src:fastify/node-js] Node.js operates on a single-thread event loop, using non-blocking I/O calls, allowing it to support tens of thousands of concurrent connections without incurring the cost of thread context switching.
[src:fastify/node-js] The design of sharing a single thread among all the requests that use the observer pattern is intended for building highly concurrent applications, where any function performing I/O must use a callback.
[src:fastify/node-js] To accommodate the single-threaded event loop, Node.js uses the libuv library—which, in turn, uses a fixed-sized thread pool that handles some of the non-blocking asynchronous I/O operations.
[src:fastify/node-js] A thread pool handles the execution of parallel tasks in Node.js.
[src:fastify/node-js] The main thread function call posts tasks to the shared task queue, which threads in the thread pool pull and execute.
[src:fastify/node-js] Inherently non-blocking system functions such as networking translate to kernel-side non-blocking sockets, while inherently blocking system functions such as file I/O run in a blocking way on their own threads.
[src:fastify/node-js] When a thread in the thread pool completes a task, it informs the main thread of this, which in turn, wakes up and executes the registered callback.
[src:fastify/node-js] A downside of this single-threaded approach is that Node.js does not allow vertical scaling by increasing the number of CPU cores of the machine it is running on without using an additional module, such as cluster, StrongLoop Process Manager, or pm2.
[src:fastify/node-js] However, developers can increase the default number of threads in the libuv thread pool.
[src:fastify/node-js] The server operating system (OS) is likely to distribute these threads across multiple cores.
[src:fastify/node-js] Another problem is that long-lasting computations and other CPU-bound tasks freeze the entire event-loop until completion.
[src:fastify/node-js] V8 is the JavaScript execution engine which was initially built for Google Chrome.
[src:fastify/node-js] It was then open-sourced by Google in 2008.
[src:fastify/node-js] Written in C++, V8 compiles JavaScript source code to native machine code at runtime.
[src:fastify/node-js] As of 2016, it also includes Ignition, a bytecode interpreter.
[src:fastify/node-js] npm is the pre-installed package manager for the Node.js server platform.
[src:fastify/node-js] It installs Node.js programs from the npm registry, organizing the installation and management of third-party Node.js programs.
[src:fastify/node-js] Node.js registers with the operating system so the OS notifies it of asynchronous I/O events such as new connections.
[src:fastify/node-js] Within the Node.js runtime, events trigger callbacks and each connection is handled as a small heap allocation.
[src:fastify/node-js] Traditionally, relatively heavyweight OS processes or threads handled each connection.
[src:fastify/node-js] Node.js uses an event loop for concurrent I/O, instead of processes or threads.
[src:fastify/node-js] In contrast to other event-driven servers, Node.js's event loop does not need to be called explicitly.
[src:fastify/node-js] Instead, callbacks are defined, and the server automatically enters the event loop at the end of the callback definition.
[src:fastify/node-js] Node.js exits the event loop when there are no further callbacks to be performed.
[src:fastify/node-js] Node.js supports WebAssembly and as of Node 14 has experimental support of WASI, the WebAssembly System Interface.
[src:fastify/node-js] Node.js provides a way to create "add-ons" via a C-based API called N-API, which can be used to produce loadable (importable) `.node` modules from source code written in C/C++.
[src:fastify/node-js] The modules can be directly loaded into memory and executed from within JS environment as simple CommonJS modules.
[src:fastify/node-js] The implementation of the N-API relies on internal C/C++ Node.js and V8 objects requiring users to import (#include) Node.js specific headers into their native source code.
[src:fastify/node-js] As the Node.js API is subject to breaking changes at a binary level, modules have to be built and shipped against specific Node.js versions to work properly.
[src:fastify/node-js] To address the issue, third parties have introduced open-sourced С/С++ wrappers on top of the API that partially alleviate the problem.
[src:fastify/node-js] They simplify interfaces, but as a side effect they may also introduce complexity which maintainers have to deal with.
[src:fastify/node-js] Even though the core functionality of Node.js resides in a JavaScript built-in library, modules written in C++ can be used to enhance capabilities and to improve performance of applications.
[src:fastify/node-js] In order to produce such modules one needs to have an appropriate C++ compiler and necessary headers (the latter are typically shipped with Node.js itself), e.g., gcc, clang or MSVC++.
[src:fastify/node-js] The N-API is similar to Java Native Interface.
[src:fastify/node-js] OpenHarmony and ArkTS also adopts N-API, with the internal implementation rewritten.
[src:fastify/node-js] In 2015, various branches of the greater Node.js community began working under the vendor-neutral Node.js Foundation.
[src:fastify/node-js] The Node.js Foundation Technical Steering Committee (TSC) is the technical governing body of the Node.js Foundation.
[src:fastify/node-js] The TSC is responsible for the core Node.js repo as well as dependent and adjacent projects.
[src:fastify/node-js] Generally the TSC delegates the administration of these projects to working groups or committees.
[src:fastify/node-js] The LTS group that manages long term supported releases is one such group.
[src:fastify/node-js] Other current groups include Website, Streams, Build, Diagnostics, i18n, Evangelism, Docker, Addon API, Benchmarking, Post-mortem, Intl, Documentation, and Testing.
[src:fastify/node-js] In August 2017, a third of the TSC members resigned due to a dispute related to the project's code of conduct.
[src:fastify/node-js] They resigned after a vote failed to remove a member from the leadership group against whom multiple complaints had been filed.
